%S A396081 2,7,19,29,31,47,59,73,79,107,127,167,191,227,239,251,263,311,347,359,
%T A396081 383,419,443,457,461,463,479,491,503,587,599,647,659,683,701,743,773,
%U A396081 839,863,887,911,937,941,971,983,991,1019,1031,1061,1063,1091,1163,1181
%N A396081 Primes p such that A381466(2p) < 2p.
%C A396081 In particular, these are the primes such that A381466(2p) = p, as this is the only possibility if A381466(2p) < 2p.
%C A396081 We conjecture that this is an infinite sequence. If so, then A394761 contains infinitely many 1's. It would also prove that there are infinitely many steps of A381466 at which we divide the index by 2. This would confirm one case of our conjecture that every positive integer is a divisor in A381466 infinitely often.
